TREATING THE MISSING VALUES The data contains a large amount of missing values. All the missing values in the categorical variables are changed to the most frequent occurring factor in the respective column and all the numeric variables are changed to it respective means.

#missing value imputation

data_free=main_data

#replacing all missing value as NA's
data_free <- replace(data_free, data_free == "", NA)
#replacing all NA's 
Mode <- function (x, na.rm) {
  xtab <- table(x)
  xmode <- names(which(xtab == max(xtab)))
  if (length(xmode) > 1) xmode <- ">1 mode"
  return(xmode)
}
for (var in 1:ncol(data_free)) 
  {
  if (class(data_free[,var])%in% c("numeric","integer")) 
    {
    data_free[is.na(data_free[,var]),var] <- mean(data_free[,var], na.rm = TRUE)
    }
  else if (class(data_free[,var]) %in% c("character", "factor")) 
    {
    data_free[is.na(data_free[,var]),var] <- tail(names(sort(table(data_free[,var]))), 1)
    }
  }
str(data_free)

LINEAR REGRESSION Data pre-processing and splitting the data set into train and test is done before building the model.

data=data_free
data=data[c('BOROUGH','ZIP.CODE','ON.STREET.NAME','NUMBER.OF.PERSONS.INJURED',
            'NUMBER.OF.PERSONS.KILLED','CONTRIBUTING.FACTOR.VEHICLE.1','CONTRIBUTING.FACTOR.VEHICLE.2',
            'VEHICLE.TYPE.CODE.1','VEHICLE.TYPE.CODE.2')]
data[sapply(data, is.character)] <- lapply(data[sapply(data, is.character)], 
                                       as.factor)
#---Regression---#
rand_data <- data[sample(nrow(data), size=3000), ]
rand_data <- na.omit(rand_data)
set.seed(123)
dat.d <- sample(1:nrow(rand_data),size=nrow(rand_data)*0.7,replace = FALSE) #random selection of 70% data.
head(dat.d)
## [1] 2463 2511 2227  526  195 2986
train.data <- rand_data[dat.d,] # 70% training data
test.data <- rand_data[-dat.d,] # remaining 30% test data
str(test.data)

DECISION TREE The data used is a subset of two of the most frequent observations in contributing factor 1. The two most frequent contributing factor are Driver Inattention/Distraction and Failure to Yield Right-of-Way. Note:- Unspecified is actually the most frequent observation here, so the most frequent observations after this character is taken.

data=data_free
data=data[c('COLLISION_ID','CRASH.TIME','BOROUGH','ZIP.CODE','ON.STREET.NAME','NUMBER.OF.PERSONS.INJURED',
            'NUMBER.OF.PERSONS.KILLED','CONTRIBUTING.FACTOR.VEHICLE.1','CONTRIBUTING.FACTOR.VEHICLE.2',
            'VEHICLE.TYPE.CODE.1','VEHICLE.TYPE.CODE.2','LOCATION','NUMBER.OF.PEDESTRIANS.INJURED','NUMBER.OF.PEDESTRIANS.KILLED',

Decision tree model Two models are build here. Model 1 uses a subset of the data set as variables and model 2 uses the full data set. The two models are compared later.

Model 1

library(rpart)
model1=rpart(CONTRIBUTING.FACTOR.VEHICLE.1~NUMBER.OF.PERSONS.INJURED+NUMBER.OF.PERSONS.KILLED+
               VEHICLE.TYPE.CODE.1+VEHICLE.TYPE.CODE.2+NUMBER.OF.PEDESTRIANS.INJURED+NUMBER.OF.PEDESTRIANS.KILLED,
             data=train.data,cp=0)
plot(model1)
text(model1)

Model 2

model2=rpart(CONTRIBUTING.FACTOR.VEHICLE.1~.
             ,data=train.data,cp=0)

Predicting the decision tree models

#testing the  model performance
pred=predict(model1,train.data,type='class')
tbl1<-table(pred, train.data $CONTRIBUTING.FACTOR.VEHICLE.1)
print(tbl1)

K-NN A K-NN algorithm is built to predict the most occurring time of accident.

data=data_free
d1=data[c('COLLISION_ID','CRASH.TIME','BOROUGH','ZIP.CODE','ON.STREET.NAME','NUMBER.OF.PERSONS.INJURED',
            'NUMBER.OF.PERSONS.KILLED','CONTRIBUTING.FACTOR.VEHICLE.1','CONTRIBUTING.FACTOR.VEHICLE.2',
            'VEHICLE.TYPE.CODE.1','VEHICLE.TYPE.CODE.2','LOCATION','NUMBER.OF.PEDESTRIANS.INJURED','NUMBER.OF.PEDESTRIANS.KILLED',
            'NUMBER.OF.CYCLIST.INJURED','NUMBER.OF.CYCLIST.KILLED','NUMBER.OF.MOTORIST.INJURED','NUMBER.OF.MOTORIST.KILLED')]

The most frequent time of accident is found to be 16:00 and 17:00 (school and office return time). A model is build on factors like borough,vehicle type etc.

tail(names(sort(table(d1$CRASH.TIME))), 3)
## [1] "15:00" "17:00" "16:00"
d1=subset(data,(data$CRASH.TIME=="16:00" | data$CRASH.TIME=="17:00"))
d1=d1[c('CRASH.TIME','BOROUGH','VEHICLE.TYPE.CODE.1','VEHICLE.TYPE.CODE.2','CONTRIBUTING.FACTOR.VEHICLE.1','CONTRIBUTING.FACTOR.VEHICLE.2'
                      )]
d1$CONTRIBUTING.FACTOR.VEHICLE.1  <- as.numeric(as.factor(d1$CONTRIBUTING.FACTOR.VEHICLE.1))
d1$CONTRIBUTING.FACTOR.VEHICLE.2 <- as.numeric(as.factor(d1$CONTRIBUTING.FACTOR.VEHICLE.2))
d1$VEHICLE.TYPE.CODE.1   <- as.numeric(as.factor(d1$VEHICLE.TYPE.CODE.1 ))
d1$VEHICLE.TYPE.CODE.2  <- as.numeric(as.factor(d1$VEHICLE.TYPE.CODE.2))
d1$BOROUGH  <- as.numeric(as.factor(d1$BOROUGH))

Splitting of train and test for K-NN Model

d1$VEHICLE.TYPE.CODE.1  <- as.numeric(as.factor(d1$VEHICLE.TYPE.CODE.1))

#splitting
rand_data <- d1[sample(nrow(d1), size=30000), ]
rand_data=rand_data[,-10]
set.seed(123)
dat.d <- sample(1:nrow(rand_data),size=nrow(rand_data)*0.7,replace = FALSE) #random selection of 70% data.
train.data <- rand_data[dat.d,] # 70% training data
test.data <- rand_data[-dat.d,] # remaining 30% test data
str(test.data)              
## 'data.frame':    9000 obs. of  6 variables:
##  $ CRASH.TIME                   : chr  "16:00" "16:00" "17:00" "16:00" ...
##  $ BOROUGH                      : num  2 2 2 2 5 2 4 3 4 2 ...
##  $ VEHICLE.TYPE.CODE.1          : num  136 127 127 3 3 122 3 3 106 122 ...
##  $ VEHICLE.TYPE.CODE.2          : num  131 137 169 4 131 115 131 4 137 131 ...
##  $ CONTRIBUTING.FACTOR.VEHICLE.1: num  11 19 55 35 55 55 11 11 7 11 ...
##  $ CONTRIBUTING.FACTOR.VEHICLE.2: num  48 48 48 31 48 48 48 48 48 48 ...
train.data[-1]=scale(train.data[-1])
test.data[-1]=scale(test.data[-1])
train.data=na.omit(train.data)
test.data=na.omit(test.data)

Model Building A k-NN model is built and is predicted on the test data set for cheking the performance of the model.

#model building
#install.packages('caTools')
library(class)
## Warning: package 'class' was built under R version 4.0.5
y_pred=knn(train=train.data[,-1],
           test=test.data[,-1],
           cl=train.data[,1],
           k=5)


head(y_pred)

—————CLUSTERING———— K-Means clustering Data Pre-processing and scaling is done before K -means clustering.

data=data_free
d<- data[sample(nrow(data), size=1000), ]
d=d[c('NUMBER.OF.PERSONS.INJURED',
                'CONTRIBUTING.FACTOR.VEHICLE.1','CONTRIBUTING.FACTOR.VEHICLE.2',
                 'VEHICLE.TYPE.CODE.1','VEHICLE.TYPE.CODE.2','NUMBER.OF.PEDESTRIANS.INJURED')]

d$CONTRIBUTING.FACTOR.VEHICLE.1  <- as.numeric(as.factor(d$CONTRIBUTING.FACTOR.VEHICLE.1))
d$CONTRIBUTING.FACTOR.VEHICLE.2 <- as.numeric(as.factor(d$CONTRIBUTING.FACTOR.VEHICLE.2))
d$VEHICLE.TYPE.CODE.1   <- as.numeric(as.factor(d$VEHICLE.TYPE.CODE.1 ))
d$VEHICLE.TYPE.CODE.2  <- as.numeric(as.factor(d$VEHICLE.TYPE.CODE.2))




d=scale(d)

Scree Plot The number of clusters are decided using an elbow method

library(factoextra)
## Warning: package 'factoextra' was built under R version 4.0.5
## Welcome! Want to learn more? See two factoextra-related books at https://goo.gl/ve3WBa
library(cluster)
fviz_nbclust(d, kmeans, method = "wss")

The number of clusters is decided as 5 from the scree plot.

K-Means model

set.seed(1)

#perform k-means clustering with k = 5 clusters
km <- kmeans(d, centers = 5, nstart = 25)

Plotting the clusters

#plot results of final k-means model
fviz_cluster(km, data = d)

The final step is to add the clusters to the original data

final_data <- cbind(d, cluster = km$cluster)

#view final data

data=data_free

         (data$CRASH.TIME=="16:00" | data$CRASH.TIME=="17:00") &
           (data$BOROUGH=="BROOKLYN" | data$BOROUGH=="QUEENS") &            (data$CONTRIBUTING.FACTOR.VEHICLE.1=="Driver Inattention/Distraction" |  data$CONTRIBUTING.FACTOR.VEHICLE.1=="Failure to Yield Right-of-Way"))

Feature scaling All the variables included are feature scaled.

rand_data <- d1[sample(nrow(d1), size=1000), ]
rand_data$CRASH.TIME  <- as.numeric(as.factor(rand_data$CRASH.TIME))
rand_data$CONTRIBUTING.FACTOR.VEHICLE.1 <- as.numeric(as.factor(rand_data$CONTRIBUTING.FACTOR.VEHICLE.1))
rand_data$VEHICLE.TYPE.CODE.1  <- as.numeric(as.factor(rand_data$VEHICLE.TYPE.CODE.1))
rand_data=rand_data[c('CRASH.TIME','BOROUGH','NUMBER.OF.PERSONS.INJURED',
                      'NUMBER.OF.PERSONS.KILLED','CONTRIBUTING.FACTOR.VEHICLE.1',
                      'VEHICLE.TYPE.CODE.1','NUMBER.OF.PEDESTRIANS.INJURED','NUMBER.OF.PEDESTRIANS.KILLED',
                      'NUMBER.OF.CYCLIST.INJURED','NUMBER.OF.CYCLIST.KILLED','NUMBER.OF.MOTORIST.INJURED','NUMBER.OF.MOTORIST.KILLED')]
set.seed(123)
dat.d <- sample(1:nrow(rand_data),size=nrow(rand_data)*0.7,replace = FALSE) #random selection of 70% data.
train.data <- rand_data[dat.d,] # 70% training data
test.data <- rand_data[-dat.d,] # remaining 30% test data
train.data[-2]=scale(train.data[-2])
test.data[-2]=scale(test.data[-2])

Model building

#building the model
#install.packages("neuralnet")
library(neuralnet)
## Warning: package 'neuralnet' was built under R version 4.0.5
## 
## Attaching package: 'neuralnet'
## The following object is masked from 'package:dplyr':
## 
##     compute
nn=neuralnet(BOROUGH~CRASH.TIME+NUMBER.OF.PERSONS.INJURED+CONTRIBUTING.FACTOR.VEHICLE.1+
               VEHICLE.TYPE.CODE.1+ NUMBER.OF.CYCLIST.INJURED+NUMBER.OF.MOTORIST.INJURED, data=train.data,
             hidden=15,act.fct="logistic",
             linear.output = FALSE)
plot(nn)

Evaluating the model

pred=compute(nn,test.data)
prob=pred$net.result
pred=ifelse(prob[,1]>0.5,"BROOKLYN","QUEENS")
new=data.frame(pred,test.data$BOROUGH)
cm = table(test.data[, 2], pred)
cm
##           pred
##            BROOKLYN QUEENS
##   BROOKLYN      174     18
##   QUEENS         92     16

The neural network was able to predict 66% of the time the borough ‘Brooklyn’ correctly, whereas a 52% in predicting the borough ‘Queens’.

Building a PCA model A PCA model three compinents are developed

# Applying PCA
#install.packages('caret')
library(caret)
## Warning: package 'caret' was built under R version 4.0.5
## Loading required package: lattice
# install.packages('e1071')
library(e1071)
pca = preProcess(x = train.data[-9], method = 'pca', pcaComp = 3)
train.data = predict(pca, train.data)
test.data = predict(pca, test.data)

head(train.data)

Three components are created and this is then used to frame a linear regression model to check the model performance. Linear regression on the pca components

l=lm(NUMBER.OF.PERSONS.INJURED~.  ,data=train.data)

The linear regression on the number of injured using the principal components are built and got an R-square of 0.01 and a adjusted R_square of 0.005. There is a no mentionable improvement in this model than the multiple linear model. Moreover the p-value>0.05.
